Leonardo DiCaprio was 27 years old during filming but portrayed a teenager convincingly.| DiCaprio, age 27, filming, teenager, portrayal | how old, when |
Catch Me If You Can was released in 2002 and is a biographical crime film.| release year, 2002, biographical film, crime, Catch Me If You Can | when, what |
Frank Abagnale Jr. was a real teenage con artist who impersonated pilots, doctors, and lawyers in the 1960s.| Frank Abagnale Jr., real person, teenage, con artist, impersonation, 1960s | who, what |
Tom Hanks plays FBI agent Carl Hanratty, who pursues Frank throughout the film.| Tom Hanks, Carl Hanratty, FBI agent, pursuit, actor | who, what |
Frank created fake Pan Am pilot credentials and used a pilot uniform to fly free on deadhead flights.| fake credentials, Pan Am, pilot, uniform, deadhead flights | how, what |
Frank started his criminal career around age 16 and stopped before turning 22.| Frank Abagnale Jr., age 16, age 22, criminal career, teenage | how old, when |
He forged checks by washing ink off legitimate checks and printing new account information.| check forgery, washing, printing, legitimate checks, fraud | how, what |
Frank passed the Louisiana Bar exam after only two weeks of study despite no formal legal education.| Louisiana Bar exam, two weeks, law study, legal education, passing test | what, how |
Frank ran away from home due to his parents’ divorce and his father’s financial troubles.| parents, divorce, father, financial troubles, motivation | why, what |
Brenda Strong is the woman Frank proposes to while posing as a lawyer.| Brenda Strong, proposal, lawyer, Louisiana, romantic interest | who, what |
Frank impersonated a doctor at a Georgia hospital using fake Harvard Medical School credentials for 11 months.| doctor, Georgia hospital, Harvard Medical School, credentials, 11 months | what, how, where, how long |
Frank’s motivation is to gain his father’s approval and avoid disappointing him.| motivation, father approval, financial problems, ambition, fear | why, what |
DiCaprio researched the real Frank Abagnale, studying interviews, dialects, and con artist psychology.| DiCaprio, research, Frank Abagnale, interviews, dialect, psychology | how, what |
Frank avoided capture by exploiting slow communication between banks and law enforcement in the 1960s.| evasion, 1960s, banks, law enforcement, communication delay | how, why |
Frank traveled across the U.S. and Europe, including France, Sweden, and Italy.| travel, United States, Europe, France, Sweden, Italy | where, what |
By age 21, Frank had accumulated eight identities, each with complete documentation.| eight identities, age 21, documents, birth certificates, credentials | how many, what |
Adults trusted Frank because his confidence and professional appearance made him seem legitimate.| trust, confidence, professional appearance, authority, adults | why, how |
Despite his success, Frank experienced loneliness and isolation throughout his criminal career.| loneliness, isolation, success, criminal career, emotional toll | what, why |
Frank Abagnale Jr. was finally caught in France after years of international fraud, partly because a girlfriend reported him.| capture, France, girlfriend report, international fraud | where, how, why |
Frank served time in French, Swedish, and U.S. prisons before working with the FBI.| prison, France, Sweden, United States, sentencing, FBI collaboration | where, what |
Leonardo DiCaprio and Tom Hanks improvised several dialogue moments to enhance realism between Frank and Carl.| improvisation, DiCaprio, Tom Hanks, dialogue, acting | how, what |
Steven Spielberg chose the project because he related to Frank’s experiences as a child of divorce.| Spielberg, directing choice, childhood, divorce, personal connection | why, what |
The real Frank Abagnale made a cameo in the film as a French police officer who arrests DiCaprio’s character.| cameo, Frank Abagnale, French officer, arrest scene | who, where, what |
Frank’s father, played by Christopher Walken, is a major emotional anchor representing approval and identity.| Christopher Walken, father figure, approval, identity, emotion | who, what, why |
The movie blends drama and comedy, making it one of Spielberg’s lightest films despite its crime themes.| tone, comedy, drama, Spielberg, light film | what, why |
Frank spent millions of dollars in forged checks across 26 countries before age 21.| forged checks, millions, 26 countries, global fraud | how many, what |
Carl Hanratty is loosely based on real FBI agent Joseph Shea, who became friends with Frank.| Carl Hanratty, Joseph Shea, FBI agent, friendship, real inspiration | who, what |
Frank’s pilot disguise worked because airlines were highly respected and rarely questioned identities in the 1960s.| pilot disguise, respect, airlines, 1960s, security | how, why |
Leonardo DiCaprio wore multiple era-accurate suits and uniforms designed to reflect Frank’s shifting identities.| costumes, suits, uniforms, identities, design | what, how |
John Williams composed the film’s jazz-influenced score to match the film’s cat-and-mouse feel.| John Williams, score, jazz, music, cat and mouse | who, what |
The film highlights how easily Frank exploited handwritten checks before modern banking systems existed.| checks, handwritten, pre-digital banking, exploitation | how, why |
